stylometry: The trade off relationship between price and demand when setting a price is when there is present an increase in price, there is a decrase in demand. The book dealt with the Madison pricing model and said "Madison's demand decreased sharply as they increased price." When prices rise, demand can fall, especially when there is competition. Businesses need to find the right price for their market knowing thier demand. Things like marketing cost and production costs also go into the pricing strategy, and also can help the demand of the product. Deciding to lower prices to raise demand to get more sold, or have a little higher price to maybe sell a little less but gain more per capita is a business decion regarding thise tradeoff. A model to develop this model is a demand-pricing model that includes the markets demands for the product as well the price of the product, including its price, manufacturing price, and other costs.
